Overview

As negotiations between CBS and Nielsen are stalled, CBS is suggesting that they may switch to using ComScores TV Essentials as an alternative data source.

This analysis looks at how data produced by ComScore differed from what was produced by Nielsen for primetime in 4Q17.

Summary

ComScore and Nielsen are most similar in household projection and, to a lesser extent, older viewers. Similarity in households is largely a function of how the ComScore data are collectedthrough set-top box data.

ComScores demographics are actually reported as HH with (e.g.Household with P18-49), indicating that rather than collecting actual demographic viewing data ComScore projects demographics based on household composition

ComScores ratings are consistently higher than Nielsens, often considerably so.

Disparities between the two systems become increasingly problematic among younger populations.

One potential inspiration for CBS promoting the potential of moving to ComScore is that it benefits far more than any other network in ComScore ratings.

By Program Average

Metrics for broadcast programs were close for household viewing with a 0.98 correlation with an average difference between the two sources of +22% (ComScore over Nielsen).

The numbers for demographic comparisons are more concerning, especially in the younger ranges.

  • P35-64 correlation is strong at 0.98 but the average difference is nearly four times that of households at +80%.
  • P25-54 correlation is borderline good at 0.92 but the average difference between ComScore and Nielsen is +143%.
  • P18-49 correlation falls to 0.86, a borderline weak figure, with an average difference of +225%.
  • P18-34 correlation of 0.71 is weak and ComScore reported viewing at over 5 times the rate of Nielsen (+426%).

By Program Genre

In addition to seeing how broadcast programs perform on average we can look at whether any genres are more impacted than others.

Sci-Fi / Fantasy programming consistently has much lower correlation between the two systems, particularly among P18-34 where correlation is 0.28. Other genres and older demos are more aligned between the two.

Broadcast Program Genre Correlation Summary Table

The low correlation between sources for Sci-Fi / Fantasy is to the genres relative detriment. While it sees some gains in ComScore they are not nearly as strong as those seen for the other genres. Dramas, for example, are typically credited with gains nearly twice the rate of SF/F.

Correlations between the two sources among cable networks were fairly tight with differences among younger viewers larger than those among households and older viewers.

Cable Network Quintiles

Because there are so many networks that have such a range of ratings it is important to look at them with more detail. Breaking the networks down into quintiles, 5 groups of 15 networks each in descending order of Nielsen P18-49 ratings, allows us to see how the impact differs by the size of the networks. We can see below that as the networks get smaller the viewing reported in ComScore gets increasingly higher.

1st Quintile

Among the top 15 networks, which range from 0.23 to 0.50, households have a reasonable correlation between sources (0.95) but the older demos arent strong: P25-54 0.75 and P35-64 0.90.

Younger demos are nowhere near acceptable: P18-34 0.33 and P18-49 0.60.

2nd Quintile

In the 2nd Quintile HH and P35-64 are both well correlated (0.99 and 0.98) and P25-54 is okay (0.93) but P18-49 is only 0.54 and P18-34 is -0.34 (negative correlation indicates direction, not strength).

Quintile 2 Cable Network Correlation Plots

3rd Quintile

Household correlation for networks in the 3rd Quintile is 0.92, P35-64 drops to below 0.9 for the first time (0.81) and P18-34 is at its lowest of all the quintiles (0.26).

4th Quintile

Correlations in the 4th Quintile are at their lowest for Households (0.87), P18-49 (0.44), P25-54 (0.29), and P35-64 (0.46).

Quintile 4 Cable Network Correlation Plots

As the average network ratings approach zero, correlations improve across the board, though none are strong.

Cable by Network Type

As there were notable differences in program genres in broadcast, cable networks were broken down by general type.

This analysis reveals that P18-34 gains outstrip those for any other demos in a move to ComScore, particularly among news networks.

Kids networks had the most to gain among any on cable, followed by sports networks. General entertainment networks would see the least amount of movement.

Correlations tended to be strongest among network types with fewer members: kids, news, and sports.

Limited Distribution networks have the lowest correlation of all network types for P18-34 (0.68), P18-49 (0.83), and P25-54 (0.87).
